        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1984-03-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1984-03-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="134"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                <head>134. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d134fn1">Source: Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">George Shultz</persName> Papers, President’s Evening
                        Reading January–March 1984. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1984-03-12">March 12, 1984</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Algeria.]</p>
                <p>2. <hi rend="italic">The Algerian Emissary</hi>. I met with the Algerian Commerce
                    Minister <persName corresp="#p_KA_2">Khellef</persName>,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d134fn2">The Shultz-Khellef conversation is in telegram 77312 to
                        Algiers, March 16. (Department of State, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        Electronic Telegrams, D840173–0806)</note> who is to deliver an oral message
                    to you tomorrow from President <persName corresp="#p_BC_1">Bendjedid</persName>.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KA_2">Khellef</persName> alleged a Moroccan turn
                    towards a military solution in the Western Sahara and argued that the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> should press King Hassan to move towards direct
                    negotiations with the Polisario. I told him we agree on the need for a
                    negotiated settlement, but believe the Moroccans recognize that a military
                    solution is unrealistic and want to proceed with the <gloss target="#t_OAU_1"
                        >OAU</gloss>-mandated referendum. <persName corresp="#p_KA_2"
                        >Khellef</persName> mentioned the situation in Lebanon but argued that the
                    Palestinian problem and the lack of acceptance of their right of
                    self-determination was at the heart of the dilemma. The <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> could help, <persName corresp="#p_KA_2">Khellef</persName> said,
                    by bringing Israel to recognize this. I told him we continue to believe that
                    Palestinian problems can be best confronted in negotiations between Jordan (with
                    Palestinian participation) and Israel.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Algeria.]</p>
            </div>
